 first by the Great Depression and then by Pearl Harbor. Demographic Angst argues that mandated normativity-as a political agenda and a social ethic-precluded explicit expression of the anxiety produced by America's radically reconfigured postwar population. Alan Nadel explores influential non-fiction books, magazine articles, and public documents in conjunction with films such as Singin' in the Rain, On the Waterfront, Sunset Boulevard, and Sayonara, to examine how these films worked through fresh anxieties that emerged during the 1950s.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Jan 2021) 0aCold War in motion pictures. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4a1950s. 4aCold War. 4aamerican culture. 4aamerican films. 4acinema. 4afilm. 4amovies. 4anormality. 4anormativity. 4apostwar. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2017z978311066609040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813565514zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813565514423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813565514.jpg  a978-3-11-066609-0  RUP eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK